WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en-GB

00:00:06.055 --> 00:00:09.320
Uber is making a renewed
'super app' push.

00:00:09.320 --> 00:00:11.120
The company that
has come to dominate

00:00:11.120 --> 00:00:14.440
western ride-hailing markets
has partnered with Expedia

00:00:14.440 --> 00:00:17.360
to allow users to book
travel within its app.

00:00:17.360 --> 00:00:21.040
The move forms part of a
longer-term ambition at Uber,

00:00:21.040 --> 00:00:23.680
which wants to keep
customers on its platform

00:00:23.680 --> 00:00:26.660
by offering them a
wide array of services.

00:00:26.660 --> 00:00:30.420
The company expanded into
food delivery in 2019,

00:00:30.420 --> 00:00:32.820
quickly followed by
groceries and shopping,

00:00:32.820 --> 00:00:34.420
and, well now travel.

00:00:34.420 --> 00:00:36.760
Uber chief executive
Dara Khosrowshahi

00:00:36.760 --> 00:00:38.920
says that the move
of Expedia is also

00:00:38.920 --> 00:00:41.920
designed to drive uptake of
the group's premium membership

00:00:41.920 --> 00:00:42.560
scheme.

00:00:42.560 --> 00:00:46.760
The group already has more than
50mn paid subscribers to its

00:00:46.760 --> 00:00:51.400
Uber One programme, but it hopes
that by offering them a range

00:00:51.400 --> 00:00:54.920
of discounts it
can drive uptake.

00:00:54.920 --> 00:00:57.080
The only problem is
that 'super apps'

00:00:57.080 --> 00:00:59.980
have had limited traction
in western markets,

00:00:59.980 --> 00:01:03.360
where users seem to be tied
to individual services.

00:01:03.360 --> 00:01:06.200
And there are other
challenges on the horizon.

00:01:06.200 --> 00:01:10.760
AI agents, which can book travel
and undertake a range of tasks

00:01:10.760 --> 00:01:15.160
on behalf of users, all threaten
to cut out middlemen like Uber.

00:01:15.160 --> 00:01:19.760
Uber is responding by trying to
drive up engagement and entice

00:01:19.760 --> 00:01:23.030
users to stay on its platform.

